Class SetExpression

  • java.lang.Object

  • @ParametersAreNonnullByDefault

public final class SetExpression
extends QueryExpression
    A set(word, ..., word) expression, which computes the union of zero or more target patterns separated by whitespace. This is intended to support the use-case in which a set of labels written to a file by a previous query expression can be modified externally, then used as input to another query, like so: 
     % buck query 'allpaths(foo, bar)' | grep ... | sed ... | awk ... >file
 % buck query "kind(qux_library, set($(
 
    The grammar currently restricts the operands of set() to being zero or more words (target
 patterns), with no intervening punctuation. In principle this could be extended to arbitrary
 expressions without grammatical ambiguity, but this seems excessively general for now.
 
    expr ::= SET '(' WORD * ')'
